✨️ What is Vintage Fashion? ✨️

When I studied fashion at university, I learned that vintage fashion was considered 20 years or older...

At the time, the professor knew how general this was and that there were different opinions on what was classified as vintage

I still consider vintage being 20 years or older while pieces over 100 years are technically antiques and probably shouldn't be worn but instead preserved as they are a piece of history 

But a slightly controversial topic revolves around "Is there a difference between Vintage and Thrift"???? 🙃

In short, the answer is YES!

But I do believe there is just a bit of grey area like when it comes to thrift shops that are full of vintage like @humana_secondhand_pt (their vintage shops) & @retrospectvintage 🤷🏻‍♀️

As a vintage lover, over the years, I've had this conversation probably a 1,000 times with thrifters & fellow vintage lovers

I don't like how vintage and thrift have been mixed up and seen as the same 😕

BUT on the other hand, I'm super HAPPY at the fact that shopping second-hand is happening (because FAST FASHION SUCKS)! 👏🏼💚🫶🏼

A win is a win! 🎉

What are your thoughts on this???

💚 Like, Save & Share this with all your second-hand loving friends!!! 

#vintagefashion #thrift #thrifting #secondhandfashion

Vintage/thrift shopping off season...Yay or nay? 🤔

I used to ONLY buy vintage or secondhand fashion during the current season or a few weeks before...A habit I picked up during my fast fashion days, and I feel like most people shop this way 🤷🏻‍♀️

But someone reminded me ages ago to shop for ALL seasons when you're vintage shopping or thrifting. 

Because NOTHING haunts us like the vintage we didn't buy! 😭

You don't want to pass up on the coat of your dreams just because it's summer or an amazing summer skirt just because it's winter.

Honestly, it took me a while to get into the habit of vintage shopping for ALL seasons

Buying or even thinking about a faux fur coat during the hot days of summer is hardly ever on my mind. Nor am I in the mood to try on a long sleeve polyester dress when I'm dropping in sweat, lol 🥵😜

But I've learned that you just have to cool off, head to the fitting room, and just try it on! 💪🏼 Also, envison yourself wearing it and how you would style it!

Shopping second-hand isn't always like shopping modern clothes or fast fashion 👗

I find that vintage shops, especially here in Lisbon, have pieces from all seasons on the sales floor, meaning you have to take your time & look just a bit closer when vintage shopping 

For this vintage coat of my dreams, I was very hesitant to even look at coats since I wouldn't be wearing them for months from now.

But I'm so glad I remembered to have an all year around approach when vintage and second-hand shopping. Because this khaki coat had been on my vintage shopping list for ages ✨️

Coat from @flamingosvintagekilolisboa 🦩🛍

Sharing is caring...SAVE & SHARE this with your vintage & thrift loving besties!! ❤️

✨️ How did you start wearing vintage fashion??? 👗

I'll share my story of how & when I started wearing vintage fashion in another post...😘

I know it's not the easiest journey & after chatting with some folks here & in real life, I was inspired to share my tips for starting to wear vintage fashion

*Like, save & share this with anyone who may need some help taking that leap on giving vintage and second-hand fashion a try 💚

So here are the ABSOLUTE BEST tips for anyone who wants to start wearing VINTAGE FASHION:

1. Start with basics like accessories (scarves, belts, hats, jewelry)

2. Visit and take your time to browse vintage and thrift shops. If you find it overwhelming, just do one section at a time or just stick with one section and come back another time to check out other sections

3. Don't be afraid to try on vintage clothes! Vintage sizes are not the same as they are today & often times something looks too big or too small on the hanger but ends up fitting perfectly 

4. If you don't see anything you like, keep checking back as shops often get in new merchandise 

5. Ask the sales staff for help. They know the items in the shop well and can help you find and discover vintage treasures

6. Mix your vintage and modern pieces together in your outfits. I feel like this is the most popular way people incorporate vintage into their personal style

7. Find a fashion era that you love and connect with. For me, I love 90s fashion, and it's mostly what I wear and shop for because of my connection to the styling and details of clothes and accessories from that era

Let me know in the comments if you would add anything or if these tips helped you at all! 🤗♻️

✨️ How did you transform your closet to be mostly vintage/thrift? ✨️ 

I don't think we talk about this enough... 

How do you make your wardrobe reflect that you are truly a vintage lover or thrift babe? 🤔

My wardobe now is 99% vintage, but getting it there wasn't an overnight thing ♻️

I abruptly stopped buying fast fashion like 10 years ago 💪🏼 

And it definitely took a few years to phase out the fast fashion clothes I already had & replace them with vintage and thrifted pieces 

Here's 3 tips that helped me transform my wardrobe to be 99% vintage & thrift: 

1. When I needed something new, I chose to buy it second-hand. For example, if I needed new tanks & tees for the summer, I bought them deadstock 

2. Slowly incorporated more vintage and thrifted pieces into my outfits while slowly phasing out wearing fast fashion. 

*Still kept my fast fashion pieces. I just started wearing them less. Added the fast fashion clothes I didn't want to my ever growing "donate" clothes piles 

3. Did a final closet survey after about a year & got rid of my remaining fast fashion clothes that I didn't wear or want at a clothing swap 

LIKE, SAVE & SHARE this!! 

*Maybe e this could be helpful to someone wondering how to incorporate more vintage and thrifted fashion into their closet 👗💚

#wearvintage #thriftlovers #wearsecondhand #choosesecondhand #vintageclothes #thrifted #vintageclothing

Do you wear vintage fashion or not yet?? 🤔

I'm sharing this because I know it's not always easy to start wearing vintage or secondhand fashion

So remember that vintage is...

1. Better for the environment 🌍

Fast fashion production is so bad for the environment in so many ways. It produces high gas emissions, pollutes the oceans, wastes an insane amount of water when making it, etc...

2. Unique style 👗

When wearing vintage, it won't be likely that someone else will be wearing the SAME thing. Plus, vintage clothes make such a special and unique fashion statement! 

3. Quality 

Vintage clothes like most things manufactured 20 + years ago were made in exceptionally better quality as things today. Vintage clothes have a much higher quality as fast fashion clothes today

✨️ When I started wearing vintage ages ago, I initially chose to give up my H&M shopping addiction and choose vintage because it was cheaper, and the pieces were unique

I was a broke New Yorker making very little working in fast fashion manufacturing, plus I was sick of twinning with people wearing the exact same clothes as me. I got so tired of hearing, "Oh, I have that top or have it in a different colour"

Then, I learned about the awful impact fast fashion has on the environment plus the unethical elements, and I  became repulsed by fast fashion and strictly wore vintage or secondhand 

I'm sharing this because I've been wearing vintage for so long, I sometimes forget how it was to start wearing vintage and second-hand

And I know some people still need that push and inspiration to wear it 💪🏼 

Like, save this for later and share this! ♻️

How important is shopping small & local to you? 🛍

I'm a vintage and secondhand lover & firmly follow the "choose secondhand first" motto 💚

BUT there are times when I need something new. In those situations, I look to shop small and local! 

Shopping small and local is super important for a list of reasons...

Here are just 3 ⤵️

1. Supports the local economy 

There's no better feeling than supporting small local businesses instead of big corporations who already have too much money, am I right?

2. Get a personal connection with the maker, seller, owner & their staff

There's nothing like chatting it up with the person who made the item you're purchasing or getting to know the owner and staff at your favourite local business 

I love shopping local markets & and I am so happy that I found @pepino.brand 🤗 The owner, Patricia, is so incredibly amazing! The stunning earrings I'm wearing in this real were hand-made by her 💙💙💙

3. Unique and quality items or services 

I personally love the quality of the very special items I find at local makers markets! Sometimes, they are limited or one of a kind pieces, and I love the unique aspect as it's one of the reasons why I love wearing vintage. 

AND

A bonus is that buying local small is better for the environment! 🌍

Local businesses tend to make more local purchases, thus using less transportation, which contributes to pollution, traffic congestion, habitat loss, and resource depletion

#shopsmall #shoplocal #supportsmallbusiness #sustainablestyle
